        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "`:help 'ignorecase'` was updated:\r\n\r\n> Ignore case in search patterns, completion, and when searching the tags file. \r\n\r\n\r\n> I think this is a microcosm of a larger problem in the help docs for options: if users can't trust the docs to tell them what an option affects comprehensively, then an underlying anxiety builds up within them about how they are affecting their system.\r\n\r\nI agree in general, but I think you are overstating the case. There are some holes, which get patched up. But also going forward, both Vim and Nvim are tending to increase \"visibility\" in the form of `:checkhealth` and programmatic mechanisms such as `mapset()`, which increase trust and reduce anxiety.\r\n\r\nI understand the anxiety and experienced it myself in the early days--that was partly what motivated me to join Neovim, which reduces surface area (legacy options and anti-features) and thus reduces user pain. \r\n\r\nThe \"coping method\" is to be more selective about which options and plugins one enables, and that continues to be important. But it's also a project goal to improve visibility and dynamic \"self-checks\" (e.g. performance checks, badly-behaving plugins, etc.).",
